1 Task 1: Data Source

These data come from an observational mother-infant cohort study conducted in western Kenya from 2012-2016. My research mentor (Arlene Dent) is the study PI.

chap <- read.csv("Project1_CHAP.csv") %>% tbl_df

                    labels=c("HUU","HEU"))

edu multi-categorical Mothers education level: none, lower primary, upper primary, or secondary or higher (3 missing observations for unknown reasons)
hosp binary Hospitalization in 1st 24mo of life: 0 = no, 1 = yes
age quantitative Age in months (range is 23.3 to 26.2)
weight quantitative Weight in kilograms (range is 8 to 16)
height quantitative Height in cm (range is 70 to 91)
HC quantitative Head circumference in cm (range is 40 to 52)
temp quantitative Axillary temperature in C (range is 35.4 to 39.8)

5 Task 5: My Subjects

The data describe a cohort of 114 children from western Kenya whose mothers were enrolled in the study during their first prenatal clinic visits and followed throughout pregnancy. At delivery, infants were enrolled and followed at 6, 10, 14, and 18 weeks, and 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age, and for any interim sick visit. Anthropometric data included here were collected at 24 months of age.

6 Task 6: My Variables

The primary predictor variable of interest is HIV exposure (all infants are HIV-uninfected: HUU are unexposed uninfected, and HEU are exposed uninfected). Studies have shown that among HIV-uninfected infants and children, those born to mothers with vs.without HIV had increased moribidity and mortality risks in the first few years of life.

PfPos is the proportion of all visits in the first 24 months of life in which the child tested positive for Plasmodium falciparum (malaria) by PCR or blood smear, and includes asymptomatic and symptomatic infections (this area of western Kenya has year-round, intense malaria transmission). UM, UM_sum, SM, SM_sum describe the number of times a child was diagnosed with uncomplicated (UM) or severe (SM) malaria in the first 24 months. Sx_malaria is a binary variable that describes whether uncomplicated malaria (UM) or severe malaria (SM) was diagnosed in the first 24 months of life.

sick, sick_sum, and sick_f describe the number of sick visits the child had in the first 24 months of life (most common diagnoses were malaria, respiratory infections, and gastrointestinal infections). MIP describes the number of times subjects mothers were diagnosed with malaria during pregnancy (none, 1, or 2 or more times).

MUAC is the mid-upper arm circumference in cm, measured at 24 months of age. MUAC is a reliable measure of nutritional status in children and is used to screen for malnutrition (MUAC may be a more reliable measure than weight, which can be influenced by acute dehydration secondary to diarrhea and gastrointestinal illness).

edu describes the highest level of education that the subjects mothers received (none, lower primary, upper primary, and secondary school or higher). This variable was chosen as a measure of socioeconomic status that might influence child nutrition and health. Overall, the level of education for mothers in this cohort was low.

hosp describes whether the child was ever hospitalized in the first 24 months of life, and reflects whether a child was diagnosed with a severe illness (most commonly with severe malaria, lower respiratory tract infection, and diarrhea/dehydration). Weight, height, head circumference, and temperature at 24 months are also included in the data.

sick_sum will be my outcome variable. Candidate predictor variables will include HIV, sex, MUAC, edu, and MIP. MUAC is a quantitative variable, and edu and MIP are multi-categorical.

Sx_malaria will be my outcome variable. Candidate predictor variables will include HIV, sex, MUAC, edu, and MIP.

This data set meets the requirement for minimum and maximum sample size (n = 114, with at least 100 rows with complete observations on all variables). Log transformation of sick_sum results in a distribution that is not much better, and problematic since 22 observations now have non-finite values.

Transforming by log(sick_sum + 1) gives a distribution that is still skewed and contains many zeros:

chap <- chap %>% mutate(sick_sum_t2 = log(sick_sum+1))

Because the transformations didnt help and the outcome sick_sum is a count, I will perform Poisson regression. I considered performing zero-inflated Poisson, however, I do not think sick_sum technically has an excess of zeros because each subject was theoretically eligible to have a sick visit.

The p value = 0, suggesting a bad fit for the model (null hypothesis is that the model is correctly specified, so the low p value suggests that we reject the null hypothesis).

The residual deviance of 309 with 106 degrees of freedom (309/106) = 2.9, which is much greater than 1 and shows that the model does not fit well, despite a few significant predictors. Can check for over-dispersion by running a quasi-poisson model.

The dispersion parameter shows us that the variance is ~2.73 times larger than the mean. Comparing the two models, we also see that though the coefficients are the same, the standard erros appear to be under-estimated by the Poisson regression compared to quasi-Poisson. So I think there may be a problem with over-dispersion here.

(From my understanding, the assumption for Poisson regression is that variance equals the expected values; for quasi-Poisson regression, the assumption is that variance is a linear function of the mean).

  • Can check to see if the variance of the residuals is proportional to the mean:
  • plot square of the residual to the predicted mean
  • black line for Poisson assumed variance
  • green line for quasi-Poisson assumed variance
  • blue curve for smoothed mean of the square of the residual
m1Diag <- data.frame(chap4, link=predict(m1, type="link"),
                     fit=predict(m1, type="response"),
                     pearson=residuals(m1,type="pearson"),
                     resid=residuals(m1,type="response"),
                     residSqr=residuals(m1,type="response")^2)

ggplot(data=m1Diag, aes(x=fit, y=residSqr)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = summary(m2)$dispersion,
              color="green") +
  stat_smooth(method="loess", se = FALSE) +
  theme_bw()

The blue line is better approximated by the green (quasi-Poisson) line as compared to the black (Poisson), however, would ideally the blue curve would be straight and collinear with the green line. Deviation from the green line shows some concern that the variance may not be proportional to the mean.

11 Task 11: Logistic Regression Model

Sx_malaria will be the outcome variable. It is a binary variable that denotes whether a subject had 1 or more episodes of symptomatic malaria (uncomplicated or severe). Candidate predictor variables include HIV, sex, MUAC, edu, and MIP.

11.1 Model selection

Spearman rho-squared plot:

plot(spearman2(Sx_malaria ~ HIV + sex + MUAC + edu + MIP, data = chap2))

Again, given the small sample size, I have limited degrees of freedom. I will focus on HIV, MUAC, and MIP.
